### Service Policy — demo: author a policy over HTTP, then evaluate against it.
### Open in VS Code (REST Client) or IntelliJ HTTP Client and run each request top-down.
### Start the app first:  ./mvnw quarkus:dev   (Docker must be running for MongoDB + OIDC)
###
### Two token variables are used (ADR-013):
###   {{admin_jwt}}  — a token whose OIDC role/scope satisfies the admin marker
###                    (default: role "authz-admin"). Needed for POST /v1/policies.
###   {{jwt}}        — any valid authenticated token. Used for evaluation.
### See "How to obtain tokens" at the bottom.

@host = http://localhost:8080
@auth_admin = Bearer {{admin_jwt}}
@auth = Bearer {{jwt}}

### 1) Create the neutral "document" policy (requires admin marker — authz-admin role)
POST {{host}}/v1/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "doc-access",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["*"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": [
    { "id": "assigned-access", "effect": "PERMIT",
      "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "IN",
        "left": {"ref": "subject.id"}, "right": {"ref": "resource.attr.assignees"} } },
    { "id": "area-scope", "effect": "PERMIT",
      "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "EQ",
        "left": {"ref": "resource.attr.area"}, "right": {"ref": "subject.attr.area"} } },
    { "id": "sealed-deny", "effect": "DENY",
      "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "EQ",
        "left": {"ref": "resource.attr.sealed"}, "right": {"value": true} } }
  ]
}

### 2) PERMIT — the subject is an assignee (replace "test-user" with the sub from your JWT)
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d1", "attributes": {"assignees": ["test-user"]}}
}

### 3) PERMIT — the subject's area matches the resource's area
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d2", "attributes": {"area": "A"}},
  "subjectAttributes": {"area": "A"}
}

### 4) DENY — the resource is sealed (deny-overrides beats the assignment permit)
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d3", "attributes": {"assignees": ["test-user"], "sealed": true}}
}

### 5) DEFAULT DENY — nothing matches (not assigned, different area, not sealed)
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d4", "attributes": {"assignees": ["someone-else"], "area": "B"}},
  "subjectAttributes": {"area": "A"}
}

### 6) DELEGATED QUERY — service-a (with pdp-client delegation marker) queries for user-x
### Replace "user-x" with any sub known to your policy data. 403 if caller lacks pdp-client.
POST {{host}}/v1/evaluate
Authorization: {{auth}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "action": "document:read",
  "resource": {"type": "document", "id": "d5"},
  "subject": "user-x"
}

### 7) CONFLICT — creating the same policyId again returns 409
POST {{host}}/v1/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "doc-access",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "document",
  "actions": ["*"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": [
    { "id": "assigned-access", "effect": "PERMIT",
      "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "IN",
        "left": {"ref": "subject.id"}, "right": {"ref": "resource.attr.assignees"} } }
  ]
}

### 8) YOUR TURN — template to author your own policy.
### Change policyId/resourceType/rules and run. Then evaluate against it (like #2-#5).
### Operators: EQ, NEQ, IN, NOT_IN, GT, GTE, LT, LTE.
### Operands: {"ref": "<path>"} (subject.id | subject.attr.* | resource.type | resource.id |
###           resource.attr.* | context.*) or {"value": <literal>}.
### Composites: {"type": "and"|"or", "conditions": [ ... ]}.
POST {{host}}/v1/policies
Authorization: {{auth_admin}}
Content-Type: application/json

{
  "policyId": "my-policy",
  "version": 1,
  "resourceType": "report",
  "actions": ["read"],
  "combiningAlgorithm": "DENY_OVERRIDES",
  "defaultEffect": "DENY",
  "rules": [
    { "id": "owner-can-read", "effect": "PERMIT",
      "condition": { "type": "comparison", "op": "EQ",
        "left": {"ref": "resource.attr.owner"}, "right": {"ref": "subject.id"} } }
  ]
}

###############################################################################
### How to obtain tokens (ADR-013)
###
### In production: obtain a Bearer token from your configured OIDC provider.
### Set the OIDC server URL: QUARKUS_OIDC_AUTH_SERVER_URL=<your-idp>
###
### Admin token (for policy authoring):
###   The token must carry the admin marker. By default, mode=role and the
###   required role is "authz-admin" (override: SERVICE_POLICY_AUTHZ_ADMIN_ROLE).
###   For Auth0 / Okta M2M tokens: set mode=scope and SERVICE_POLICY_AUTHZ_ADMIN_SCOPE.
###
### Delegation token (for delegated queries via the "subject" field):
###   The token must carry the delegation marker. By default, mode=role and the
###   required role is "pdp-client" (override: SERVICE_POLICY_AUTHZ_DELEGATION_ROLE).
###
### VS Code REST Client — create docs/http-client.env.json (git-ignored):
###   {
###     "dev": {
###       "admin_jwt": "<admin token from your IdP>",
###       "jwt":       "<regular user token from your IdP>"
###     }
###   }
###   then pick the "dev" environment in the status bar.
###
### IntelliJ HTTP Client — create http-client.private.env.json (git-ignored):
###   { "dev": { "admin_jwt": "<admin token>", "jwt": "<user token>" } }
###############################################################################
